    <h1 id="great-blue-heron-habitat-wetlands-waterways-and-surprising-places">Great Blue Heron Habitat: Wetlands, Waterways, and Surprising Places</h1>
<p>The Great Blue Heron adapts to almost any wetland habitat in its range. Fresh and saltwater marshes, mangrove swamps, flooded meadows, lake edges, riverbanks, tidal flats, estuaries, and shorelines all qualify — and the bird is comfortable in heavily developed areas as long as fish-bearing water is present.<sup id="fnref:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup> It lives comfortably in both freshwater and saltwater systems and also forages in grasslands and agricultural fields, where it stalks frogs and small mammals.<sup id="fnref:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="foraging-habitat">Foraging habitat</h2>
<p>The classic image is a heron standing belly-deep at the edge of calm, shallow water — typically less than 30 cm (12 in) deep — but the menu of foraging sites is broad: pond and lake margins, slow rivers and streams, salt ponds, mudflats at ebb tide, irrigation ditches, flooded fields, and even offshore kelp beds, where coastal birds perch on floating kelp waiting for fish.<sup id="fnref:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup><sup id="fnref:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup> Upland foraging is common, especially in winter: Pacific birds move into grasslands to hunt rodents after October, and an Idaho study found voles made up 24–40% of the local diet.<sup id="fnref:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup><sup id="fnref:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup> Their large size lets them wade deeper water than other wading birds can exploit.<sup id="fnref:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="nesting-habitat">Nesting habitat</h2>
<p>Nesting has a different logic. Colonies are usually placed within <strong>2–4 miles of good feeding areas</strong> (up to about 10 miles in some regions), in spots that are hard for predators and people to reach: wooded swamps, islands, beaver flowages full of standing dead trees, or the crowns of the tallest trees available.<sup id="fnref2:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup><sup id="fnref2:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup> Most nests sit 20–60 feet up, but herons also nest in low shrubs, mangroves, on the ground of predator-free islands, and on human structures — duck blinds, channel markers, and purpose-built nest platforms.<sup id="fnref3:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup><sup id="fnref2:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup> On the Pacific coast, bigleaf maple, red alder, black cottonwood, and London plane trees are favored; in Virginia, loblolly pine and sycamore.<sup id="fnref2:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup><sup id="fnref:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup> Water beneath or beside nest trees provides a buffer against raccoons and other mammalian predators.<sup id="fnref2:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="the-beaver-connection">The beaver connection</h2>
<p>Beavers are unlikely allies. In North Carolina, a surge in beaver ponds since about 1980 (along with new reservoirs) created freshwater wetlands that let Great Blue Herons expand nesting into most counties away from the mountains; Massachusetts likewise credits rising beaver populations with creating the dead-tree swamps herons favor for rookeries.<sup id="fnref3:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup><sup id="fnref:9"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:9">9</a></sup> The flip side appears in Maine, where state biologists list the loss of beaver flowages — through beaver trapping — as a contributor to nesting habitat loss and colony abandonment.<sup id="fnref:10"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:10">10</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="habitat-requirements-summarized">Habitat requirements, summarized</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Need</th>
<th>What it looks like</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Food</td>
<td>Shallow, calm, fish/amphibian-rich water within a few miles of the colony<sup id="fnref4:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup><sup id="fnref3:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Nest sites</td>
<td>Tall trees (living or dead), often over water; isolated swamps or islands; sometimes ground or platforms<sup id="fnref5:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup><sup id="fnref3:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Security</td>
<td>Low disturbance, especially early in nesting season; visual screening and buffers of 100 m+ from foot traffic<sup id="fnref4:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Roosting</td>
<td>Secluded tall trees; communal night roosts of 5–20 birds outside breeding season<sup id="fnref3:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup><sup id="fnref:11"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:11">11</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Winter</td>
<td>Ice-free water — the single factor that decides whether a heron can stay north<sup id="fnref:12"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:12">12</a></sup></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
